  <h1>What to Do After a Pedestrian Accident</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>1. Get medical care immediately</h2><p>Pedestrian accident injuries are often more severe than they appear at the scene. Adrenaline masks pain. Go to the emergency room, even if you feel okay. Internal injuries, TBI symptoms, and fractures may not be apparent for hours. Your medical records from the day of the accident are the foundation of your claim.</p>
  <h2>2. Call 911 and stay at the scene</h2><p>A police report documents the driver&rsquo;s information, witnesses, and the officer&rsquo;s initial assessment of fault. Get the driver&rsquo;s insurance information, license plate, and driver&rsquo;s license number. Photograph the scene, the vehicle, your injuries, and any traffic signals.</p>
  <h2>3. Gather witness information</h2><p>Eyewitnesses who saw the accident are critical. Get names and phone numbers. Nearby businesses may have surveillance cameras — request preservation of footage immediately (most systems overwrite within 30–90 days).</p>
  <h2>4. Do not give a recorded statement to the driver&rsquo;s insurer</h2><p>The at-fault driver&rsquo;s insurance will contact you quickly. Do not give a recorded statement without an attorney. Adjusters are trained to elicit statements that reduce your claim. Say only that you were injured and that you will have your attorney contact them.</p>
  <h2>5. Contact a personal injury attorney</h2><p>Pedestrian accident attorneys work on contingency (no fee unless you win) and have experience dealing with auto insurers. Contact one before any settlement offer — initial offers are almost always far below the value of serious injuries.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-pedestrian-accident-claims-work">how claims work</a> and <a href="/guides/pedestrian-accident-misconceptions">common misconceptions</a>.</p>
